SIMPLE: iris
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Iris
<hw>I"ris</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> E.
<plw>Irises</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, L. <plw>Irides</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[L. <ets>iris</ets>, <ets>iridis</ets>, the goddess, Gr. <?/, <?/,
the rainbow, iris of the eye, the plant Iris. Cf. <er>Orris</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Class. Myth.)</fld> <def>The goddess of the rainbow,
and swift-footed messenger of the gods.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The rainbow.</def> <rj><au>Sir T.
Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An appearance resembling the rainbow; a prismatic
play of colors.</def> <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The contractile membrane
perforated by the pupil, and forming the colored portion of the eye. See
<er>Eye</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of plants having showy
flowers and bulbous or tuberous roots, of which the flower-de-luce
(<xex>fleur-de-lis</xex>), orris, and other species of flag are
examples. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Flower-de-luce</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>See <er>Fleur-de-lis</er>,
2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>the inner circle of an oscillated
color spot.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>same as <er>iris diaphragm</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Irisated</ent>⟦br⟧
